      "span_text": "Base deficit is used as a reliable indicator of blood loss, adequacy of resuscitation, and mortality in trauma patients, and it is a more sensitive marker of hypovolemia than are traditional vital signs.  In addition, patients with evidence of considerable ischemic acidosis (ie, lower levels of base deficit and elevated lactate levels) in the initial 24 hours following major trauma are significantly more likely to develop ARDS in the first 4 days after injury."
